rgangenheitsverl.|location=Berlin|isbn=978-3-86408-068-5}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Charles|last1= Grant|first2=Michael |last2=Youens|title=The Black Watch|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1PBP-ocpbM4C&pg=PP1|date=15 June 1971|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-0-85045-053-8}}\n* {{cite book|first=James |last=Grant|title=The Black Watch or, Forty-Second Highlanders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=omvMCG7WTIQC&lpg=PP1&dq=Black%20Watch&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Elibron.com|isbn=978-1-4021-7481-0|date=1999-01-01}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Schofield|first1=Victoria|title=The Highland Furies: The Black Watch 1739\u20131899|publisher=Quercus Publishing|isbn=978-1-84916-918-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ligSjYClRYAC&dq=highland+furies|date=26 April 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Black Watch}}\n* [http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/26341.aspx 3 SCOTS] on British Army website\n* [http://www.theblackwatch.co.uk/ The Black Watch Website]\n* [http://www.blackwatchcanada.com/ Black Watch Canada]\n*The Black Watch Castle & Museum - [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/browse/r/h/A13532431 catalogues for archive collections]\n\n{{Royal Regiments of Scotland}}\n{{British infantry regiments World War I}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Battalions of Korean War]]\n[[Category:Battalions of the British Army]]\n[[Category:Highland regiments]]\n[[Category:Military of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in British Somaliland in World War II]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the United Kingdom in the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Royal Regiment of Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "DocWatson42", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Performed minor cleanup.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Watch"}
{"title_page": "Elio Perlman", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{advertisement|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color = #892003 \n| name = Elio Perlman\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| first = ''[[Call Me by Your Name (novel)|Call Me by Your Name]]''\n| last = ''[[Find Me (novel)|Find Me]]''\n| creator = [[Andr\u00e9 Aciman]]\n| portrayer = [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]] (film)\n| adapted_by = [[Luca Guadagnino]] (director)<br>[[James Ivory]] (writer)\n| gender = Male\n| nationality = Italian\n| occupation = Student (''Call Me by Your Name'')<br>Pianist (''Find Me'') \n| significant_other = Oliver \n| family = Sami Perlman (father)<br> Annella Perlman (mother)\n}}\n\n'''Elio Perlman''' is a fictional character and the [[protagonist]] of the 2007 novel ''[[Call Me by Your Name (novel)|Call Me by Your Name]]'' and its 2019 follow-up novel ''[[Find Me (novel)|Find Me]]'', created by [[Andr\u00e9 Aciman]].\n\nPerlman is portrayed by [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]] in the 2017 [[Academy Award]]-winning film [[Call Me by Your Name (film)|adaptation of the same name]]. Directed by [[Luca Guadagnino]] and written by [[James Ivory]], the film follows Elio Perlman, a precocious 17-year-old as he spends the summer of 1983 with his family in their 17th-century villa in Lombardy, Italy. He soon meets Oliver, a handsome doctoral student who's working as an intern for Elio's father. Amid the sun-drenched splendor of their surroundings, romance blossoms between Elio and Oliver as they discover the heady beauty of awakening desire over the course of a summer that will alter their lives forever.\n \nFor his portrayal, Chalamet received nominations for an [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]], a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|BAFTA Award]], a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe Award]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]], and a [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Critics' Choice Award]], all for Best Actor. He also won numerous critics awards, namely [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor|New York Film Critics Circle Award]], [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Actor|Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award]] and [[London Film Critics' Circle Award for Actor of the Year|London Film Critics' Circle Award]].\n\n==Characterization==\n\nElio Perlman is a 17-year-old Jewish-American boy. He is intellectual and artistic, spending a great deal of time playing piano, perfecting classical pieces as well as composing his own. He is sensitive and charming, although at times, showing naivety and unable to articulate all that he feels. He is the protagonist of the coming-of-age story, a teenager on the brink of manhood, passionate and libidinous, experiencing love for the first time.\n\nThe son of Jewish-American intellectual scholars, Elio is an intelligent young man who is trilingual, well-read, and a talented musician. He spends his summers working on classical scores, playing the guitar and piano, reading, swimming with friends, and playing tennis. He is initially attracted to and in sexual relationship with Marzia. When he meets Oliver though, his attraction eclipses his other interests. During Oliver's stay in his family's house, Elio tries to spend as much time as possible in the presence of this alluring man. Although he understands he's attracted to Oliver, it takes time for Elio to decide if he wants anything to happen between them.ele gosta de dar o cu\n\n==Relationships==\n\n===Marzia===\n\nMarzia is Elio's Italian girlfriend. The two share a reciprocity love and mutual attraction towards one another. After meeting Oliver, Mariza is confused by his apparent ambivalence about her. While she never gets angry at him explicitly, she is clearly wounded by his indifference towards her. When Oliver later leaves, Marzia realizes that Elio has been in love with Oliver all along, she tells him that she is not upset and offers him her friendship alongside their relationship. Fifteen years later, the pair are mentioned to have married, Marzia maintaining a tender and heartfelt relationship with Elio.\n\n===Oliver===\n\nOliver is a 24-year-old Jewish-American graduate student who is writing and researching with Elio's father in Italy. He is a cheerful, breezy person, although often unpredictable and impulsive, contrasting to Elio's personality. While he is intellectual and thoughtful, he is also more confident and sociable than Elio, often participating in social drinking, playing games, and seducing young women without care. Where Elio is more hesitant and introverted, Oliver chooses to cope with his confusion about his own emotions by throwing himself at things impulsively. Unlike Elio, he did not have an accepting upbringing and experiences more shame and ambivalence about his homosexual feelings.\n\nSoon enough, Elio feels tortured by the idea that his attraction might slip by unnoticed, so he tells Oliver how he feels. In doing so, he shatters the indecision and relational calculations that have been tormenting him for weeks, though even when he and Oliver finally kiss, he isn't sure what to make of their connection. Similarly, he feels confused after they have sex, ultimately experiencing something like shame even though he's glad to have acted on his feelings.\n\nIn the beginning of their acquaintanceship, Oliver and Elio do not quite know what to think of one another, or how to deal with their mutual attraction. In the early days of their courtship, they find it easiest to talk about intellectual and artistic matters. Oliver asks Elio about the music he is playing, lightly challenging his claims about the compositions. He asks Elio what he thinks of a sentence from his academic work, and they engage in light banter about intellectual matters. Thus, before their connection becomes physical or romantic, it is based on matters of the mind and questions of aesthetics.\n\n===Sami Perlman===\n\nSami Perlman is an archeology professor and Elio's father. He invites grad student Oliver to live with his family in Italy over the summer. He is passionate and warm-hearted, smiling genially at nearly every opportunity, and encouraging his son's friendship and eventual affair with Oliver. Towards the end of the film and novel, he expresses his approval for Elio and Oliver's relationship, suggesting that the love they share something very special, and urging Elio not to repress his feelings about their relationship.\n\n==Casting==\nIn 2015, it was reported that [[Shia LaBeouf]] and [[Greta Scacchi]] were set to be cast in a film adaptation of the novel.<ref name=\"NYTivoryprofile\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/11/t-magazine/james-ivory-house.html|title=James Ivory's Home Befits His Extraordinary Life|first=Nancy|last=Hass|work=[[The New York Times Style Magazine]]|date=September 11, 2015|accessdate=May 8, 2017|page=M2191|publication-date=September 13, 2015|issue=T|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407002210/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/11/t-magazine/james-ivory-house.html|archivedate=April 7, 2017}}</ref> In September 2016, Ivory had confirmed that the duo were no longer involved in the project. Ivory said he got along with LaBeouf, who had read for the film in New York City, but the production company later felt the actor was unsuitable after the public and media attention regarding his \"various troubles\".<ref name=\"Heat\" /> Ivory thought Scacchi and LeBeouf read well together and could have made it into the film, but the company disagreed.<ref name=\"Heat\">{{cite web|url=https://heatst.com/world/james-ivory-on-howards-end-not-being-able-to-work-with-shia-labeouf-and-tom-hiddleston/|title=James Ivory on 'Howards End', Not Being Able to Work with Shia LaBeouf and Tom Hiddleston|first=Tom|last=Teodorczuk|work=[[Heat Street]]|date=September 23, 2016|accessdate=May 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704170257/https://heatst.com/world/james-ivory-on-howards-end-not-being-able-to-work-with-shia-labeouf-and-tom-hiddleston/|archivedate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Chalamet was introduced to Guadagnino by Brian Swardstrom \u2013 husband of producer [[Peter Spears]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/global/berlinale-luca-guadagnino-call-me-by-your-name-1201986720/|title=Berlinale: Luca Guadagnino on Why 'Call Me by Your Name' Strikes Such Deep Chords|first=Nick|last=Vivarelli|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 13, 2017|accessdate=October 6, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818011008/http://variety.com/2017/film/global/berlinale-luca-guadagnino-call-me-by-your-name-1201986720/|archivedate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> \u2013 who immediately felt the actor had \"the ambition, the intelligence, the sensitivity, the naivety, and the artistry\" that was required in order to play Elio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenprism.com/insights/article/luca-guadagnino-talks-call-me-by-your-name-at-the-55th-new-york-film-festiv|title=Luca Guadagnino Discusses 'Call Me By Your Name' at the 55th New York Film Festival|work=Screenprism|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=October 11, 2017|first=Meghan|last=Gilligan|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203015503/http://screenprism.com/insights/article/luca-guadagnino-talks-call-me-by-your-name-at-the-55th-new-york-film-festiv|archivedate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> Chalamet had already read Aciman's novel prior to being cast and described it as \"a window into a young person\".<ref name=\"racy\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/features/actor-timothee-chalamet-1202579558/|title=Timothee Chalamet on His Racy Sex Scene in 'Call Me By Your Name'|first=Ramin|last=Setoodeh|date=October 4, 2017|accessdate=October 4, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004194655/http://variety.com/2017/film/features/actor-timothee-chalamet-1202579558/|archivedate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> His character, 17-year-old Elio, is fluent in three languages: English, French and Italian. Upon his arrival in Italy, Chalamet\u2014who already spoke French fluently and had played piano and guitar for years<ref name=\"mongrel\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.mongrelmedia.com/MongrelMedia/files/9a/9a539f31-154b-4d83-a3ce-e421191266fb.pdf|title=Mongrel Presents: Call Me by Your Name|publisher=[[Mongrel Media]]|first=Bonne|last=Smith|accessdate=October 17, 2017|location=Toronto, Ontario|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028132924/http://www.mongrelmedia.com/MongrelMedia/files/9a/9a539f31-154b-4d83-a3ce-e421191266fb.pdf|archivedate=October 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"interviewmag\">{{cite web|url=https://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/timothee-chalamet|title=Timothee Chalamet|first=Matthew|last=McConaughey|author-link=Matthew McConaughey|date=June 2, 2017|accessdate=October 4, 2017|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919200019/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/timothee-chalamet|archivedate=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\u2014prepared for his role with a schedule of daily lessons in Italian, gym workouts three times a week,<ref name=\"mongrel\"/> and by working with composer Roberto Solci.<ref name=\"mongrel\" />\n\n==Reception==\n\n''[[The Economist]]'' described the tension \"between pain and pleasure\" in the film and praised Chalamet portrayal of Elio, saying that he \"evokes so many shades of humanity, portraying a path of youthful self-discovery that is more raw, unhinged, and ultimately honest than many actors could manage\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=N.E.G.|title=\"Call Me By Your Name\" is a work of beauty|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2017/09/what-lies-beneath|accessdate=September 12, 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=September 8, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912000305/https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2017/09/what-lies-beneath|archivedate=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', [[Richard Lawson (writer)|Richard Lawson]] wrote that\n\"Chalamet has the bearing of a natural; he\u2019s deeply committed to his character\" and that he also manages to \"infuse Elio with something of himself, too, as the best movie stars do\". He also writes that \"Chalamet seems to know that he\u2019s got an innate charm, a boyish grace, and he uses that to striking effect. Elio, soulful and impetuous and a little bratty, is a kid you\u2019ve known, a kid you wanted to be, a kid you care and root for\", before calling his portrayal of Elio \"a mature and thoughtful performance, and it augurs great things for Chalamet going forward\".\n\n===Performance recognition===\n\nAt the age of 21, Chalamet became the [[List of Academy Award records#Age-related records|youngest]] [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] nominee [[12th Academy Awards|since 1939]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-oscars-james-ivory-adapted-screenplay-20180304-story.html|work=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|title=James Ivory becomes Oscar's oldest winner with 'Call Me by Your Name'|date=March 4, 2018|accessdate=March 4, 2018|first1=Mark|last1=Olsen|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305162848/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-oscars-james-ivory-adapted-screenplay-20180304-story.html|archivedate=March 5, 2018}}</ref> in addition to nominations at [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|BAFTA]], the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globes]], the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild]], and a [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Critics' Choice Awards]] for Best Actor.\n\nAt the [[33rd Independent Spirit Awards]], Chalamet won the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Male Lead|Best Male Lead Award]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/PressReleasesSA/2018_SA_NomineeRelease_FINAL.pdf|title=33rd Film Independent Spirits Nominations Announced|publisher=[[Independent Spirit Awards]]|date=November 21, 2017|accessdate=November 21, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207071727/https://s3.amazonaws.com/PressReleasesSA/2018_SA_NomineeRelease_FINAL.pdf|archivedate=December 7, 2017|url-status=live|type=Press release|location=Los Angeles}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmindependent.org/press/press-releases/2018-film-independent-spirit-awards-winners-announced/|title=2018 Film Independent Spirit Awards Winners Announced|publisher=[[Independent Spirit Awards]]|date=March 3, 2018|location=Los Angeles|accessdate=March 3, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304021242/https://www.filmindependent.org/press/press-releases/2018-film-independent-spirit-awards-winners-announced/|archivedate=March 4, 2018|url-status=dead|type=Press release}}</ref> other accolades he won included; The [[National Board of Review]], the [[Gotham Independent Film Awards]] and the [[Hollywood Film Awards]] for Breakout Actor, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gettell|first1=Oliver|title=''Call Me By Your Name'' takes top prize at 2017 Gotham Awards|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/11/27/gotham-awards-2017-winners-list/|accessdate=November 27, 2017|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207224507/http://ew.com/movies/2017/11/27/gotham-awards-2017-winners-list/|archivedate=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodawards.com/2017-honorees/|title= 2017 Honorees|publisher=[[Hollywood Film Awards]]|accessdate=October 19, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022082519/https://www.hollywoodawards.com/2017-honorees/|archivedate=October 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[IndieWire]], in a series of articles regarding the best of film [[2010s in film|in the 2010s]], named Chalamet's portrayal of Elio as the 39th best film performance of the 2010s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/gallery/best-acting-movies-2010s-performances/|title=The 50 Best Movie Performances of the Decade|last=Zilko|first=David Ehrlich,Kate Erbland,Eric Kohn,Anne Thompson,Chris O'Falt,Tambay Obenson,Christian Blauvelt,Christian|last2=Ehrlich|first2=David|date=2019-07-23|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28|last3=Erbland|first3=Kate|last4=Kohn|first4=Eric|last5=Thompson|first5=Anne|last6=O'Falt|first6=Chris|last7=Obenson|first7=Tambay|last8=Blauvelt|first8=Christian|last9=Zilko|first9=Christian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Call Me by Your Name}}\n\n[[Category:Call Me by Your Name]]\n[[Category:Drama film characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional bisexual males]]\n[[Category:Fictional Jews]]\n[[Category:Fictional LGBT characters in film]]\n[[Category:Fictional LGBT characters in literature]]\n[[Category:Fictional musicians]]\n[[Category:Fictional North American people]]\n[[Category:Fictional pianists]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in literature]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{advertisement|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color = #892003 \n| name = Elio Perlman\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| first = ''[[Call Me by Your Name (novel)|Call Me by Your Name]]''\n| last = ''[[Find Me (novel)|Find Me]]''\n| creator = [[Andr\u00e9 Aciman]]\n| portrayer = [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]] (film)\n| adapted_by = [[Luca Guadagnino]] (director)<br>[[James Ivory]] (writer)\n| gender = Male\n| nationality = Italian\n| occupation = Student (''Call Me by Your Name'')<br>Pianist (''Find Me'') \n| significant_other = Oliver \n| family = Sami Perlman (father)<br> Annella Perlman (mother)\n}}\n\n'''Elio Perlman''' is a fictional character and the [[protagonist]] of the 2007 novel ''[[Call Me by Your Name (novel)|Call Me by Your Name]]'' and its 2019 follow-up novel ''[[Find Me (novel)|Find Me]]'', created by [[Andr\u00e9 Aciman]].\n\nPerlman is portrayed by [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]] in the 2017 [[Academy Award]]-winning film [[Call Me by Your Name (film)|adaptation of the same name]]. Directed by [[Luca Guadagnino]] and written by [[James Ivory]], the film follows Elio Perlman, a precocious 17-year-old as he spends the summer of 1983 with his family in their 17th-century villa in Lombardy, Italy. He soon meets Oliver, a handsome doctoral student who's working as an intern for Elio's father. Amid the sun-drenched splendor of their surroundings, romance blossoms between Elio and Oliver as they discover the heady beauty of awakening desire over the course of a summer that will alter their lives forever.\n \nFor his portrayal, Chalamet received nominations for an [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]], a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|BAFTA Award]], a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe Award]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]], and a [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Critics' Choice Award]], all for Best Actor. He also won numerous critics awards, namely [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor|New York Film Critics Circle Award]], [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Actor|Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award]] and [[London Film Critics' Circle Award for Actor of the Year|London Film Critics' Circle Award]].\n\n==Characterization==\n\nElio Perlman is a 17-year-old Jewish-American boy. He is intellectual and artistic, spending a great deal of time playing piano, perfecting classical pieces as well as composing his own. He is sensitive and charming, although at times, showing naivety and unable to articulate all that he feels. He is the protagonist of the coming-of-age story, a teenager on the brink of manhood, passionate and libidinous, experiencing love for the first time.\n\nThe son of Jewish-American intellectual scholars, Elio is an intelligent young man who is trilingual, well-read, and a talented musician. He spends his summers working on classical scores, playing the guitar and piano, reading, swimming with friends, and playing tennis. He is initially attracted to and in sexual relationship with Marzia. When he meets Oliver though, his attraction eclipses his other interests. During Oliver's stay in his family's house, Elio tries to spend as much time as possible in the presence of this alluring man. Although he understands he's attracted to Oliver, it takes time for Elio to decide if he wants anything to happen between them.\n\n==Relationships==\n\n===Marzia===\n\nMarzia is Elio's Italian girlfriend. The two share a reciprocity love and mutual attraction towards one another. After meeting Oliver, Mariza is confused by his apparent ambivalence about her. While she never gets angry at him explicitly, she is clearly wounded by his indifference towards her. When Oliver later leaves, Marzia realizes that Elio has been in love with Oliver all along, she tells him that she is not upset and offers him her friendship alongside their relationship. Fifteen years later, the pair are mentioned to have married, Marzia maintaining a tender and heartfelt relationship with Elio.\n\n===Oliver===\n\nOliver is a 24-year-old Jewish-American graduate student who is writing and researching with Elio's father in Italy. He is a cheerful, breezy person, although often unpredictable and impulsive, contrasting to Elio's personality. While he is intellectual and thoughtful, he is also more confident and sociable than Elio, often participating in social drinking, playing games, and seducing young women without care. Where Elio is more hesitant and introverted, Oliver chooses to cope with his confusion about his own emotions by throwing himself at things impulsively. Unlike Elio, he did not have an accepting upbringing and experiences more shame and ambivalence about his homosexual feelings.\n\nSoon enough, Elio feels tortured by the idea that his attraction might slip by unnoticed, so he tells Oliver how he feels. In doing so, he shatters the indecision and relational calculations that have been tormenting him for weeks, though even when he and Oliver finally kiss, he isn't sure what to make of their connection. Similarly, he feels confused after they have sex, ultimately experiencing something like shame even though he's glad to have acted on his feelings.\n\nIn the beginning of their acquaintanceship, Oliver and Elio do not quite know what to think of one another, or how to deal with their mutual attraction. In the early days of their courtship, they find it easiest to talk about intellectual and artistic matters. Oliver asks Elio about the music he is playing, lightly challenging his claims about the compositions. He asks Elio what he thinks of a sentence from his academic work, and they engage in light banter about intellectual matters. Thus, before their connection becomes physical or romantic, it is based on matters of the mind and questions of aesthetics.\n\n===Sami Perlman===\n\nSami Perlman is an archeology professor and Elio's father. He invites grad student Oliver to live with his family in Italy over the summer. He is passionate and warm-hearted, smiling genially at nearly every opportunity, and encouraging his son's friendship and eventual affair with Oliver. Towards the end of the film and novel, he expresses his approval for Elio and Oliver's relationship, suggesting that the love they share something very special, and urging Elio not to repress his feelings about their relationship.\n\n==Casting==\nIn 2015, it was reported that [[Shia LaBeouf]] and [[Greta Scacchi]] were set to be cast in a film adaptation of the novel.<ref name=\"NYTivoryprofile\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/11/t-magazine/james-ivory-house.html|title=James Ivory's Home Befits His Extraordinary Life|first=Nancy|last=Hass|work=[[The New York Times Style Magazine]]|date=September 11, 2015|accessdate=May 8, 2017|page=M2191|publication-date=September 13, 2015|issue=T|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407002210/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/11/t-magazine/james-ivory-house.html|archivedate=April 7, 2017}}</ref> In September 2016, Ivory had confirmed that the duo were no longer involved in the project. Ivory said he got along with LaBeouf, who had read for the film in New York City, but the production company later felt the actor was unsuitable after the public and media attention regarding his \"various troubles\".<ref name=\"Heat\" /> Ivory thought Scacchi and LeBeouf read well together and could have made it into the film, but the company disagreed.<ref name=\"Heat\">{{cite web|url=https://heatst.com/world/james-ivory-on-howards-end-not-being-able-to-work-with-shia-labeouf-and-tom-hiddleston/|title=James Ivory on 'Howards End', Not Being Able to Work with Shia LaBeouf and Tom Hiddleston|first=Tom|last=Teodorczuk|work=[[Heat Street]]|date=September 23, 2016|accessdate=May 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704170257/https://heatst.com/world/james-ivory-on-howards-end-not-being-able-to-work-with-shia-labeouf-and-tom-hiddleston/|archivedate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Chalamet was introduced to Guadagnino by Brian Swardstrom \u2013 husband of producer [[Peter Spears]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/global/berlinale-luca-guadagnino-call-me-by-your-name-1201986720/|title=Berlinale: Luca Guadagnino on Why 'Call Me by Your Name' Strikes Such Deep Chords|first=Nick|last=Vivarelli|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 13, 2017|accessdate=October 6, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818011008/http://variety.com/2017/film/global/berlinale-luca-guadagnino-call-me-by-your-name-1201986720/|archivedate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> \u2013 who immediately felt the actor had \"the ambition, the intelligence, the sensitivity, the naivety, and the artistry\" that was required in order to play Elio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenprism.com/insights/article/luca-guadagnino-talks-call-me-by-your-name-at-the-55th-new-york-film-festiv|title=Luca Guadagnino Discusses 'Call Me By Your Name' at the 55th New York Film Festival|work=Screenprism|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=October 11, 2017|first=Meghan|last=Gilligan|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203015503/http://screenprism.com/insights/article/luca-guadagnino-talks-call-me-by-your-name-at-the-55th-new-york-film-festiv|archivedate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> Chalamet had already read Aciman's novel prior to being cast and described it as \"a window into a young person\".<ref name=\"racy\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/features/actor-timothee-chalamet-1202579558/|title=Timothee Chalamet on His Racy Sex Scene in 'Call Me By Your Name'|first=Ramin|last=Setoodeh|date=October 4, 2017|accessdate=October 4, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004194655/http://variety.com/2017/film/features/actor-timothee-chalamet-1202579558/|archivedate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> His character, 17-year-old Elio, is fluent in three languages: English, French and Italian. Upon his arrival in Italy, Chalamet\u2014who already spoke French fluently and had played piano and guitar for years<ref name=\"mongrel\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.mongrelmedia.com/MongrelMedia/files/9a/9a539f31-154b-4d83-a3ce-e421191266fb.pdf|title=Mongrel Presents: Call Me by Your Name|publisher=[[Mongrel Media]]|first=Bonne|last=Smith|accessdate=October 17, 2017|location=Toronto, Ontario|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028132924/http://www.mongrelmedia.com/MongrelMedia/files/9a/9a539f31-154b-4d83-a3ce-e421191266fb.pdf|archivedate=October 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"interviewmag\">{{cite web|url=https://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/timothee-chalamet|title=Timothee Chalamet|first=Matthew|last=McConaughey|author-link=Matthew McConaughey|date=June 2, 2017|accessdate=October 4, 2017|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919200019/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/timothee-chalamet|archivedate=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\u2014prepared for his role with a schedule of daily lessons in Italian, gym workouts three times a week,<ref name=\"mongrel\"/> and by working with composer Roberto Solci.<ref name=\"mongrel\" />\n\n==Reception==\n\n''[[The Economist]]'' described the tension \"between pain and pleasure\" in the film and praised Chalamet portrayal of Elio, saying that he \"evokes so many shades of humanity, portraying a path of youthful self-discovery that is more raw, unhinged, and ultimately honest than many actors could manage\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=N.E.G.|title=\"Call Me By Your Name\" is a work of beauty|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2017/09/what-lies-beneath|accessdate=September 12, 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=September 8, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912000305/https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2017/09/what-lies-beneath|archivedate=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', [[Richard Lawson (writer)|Richard Lawson]] wrote that\n\"Chalamet has the bearing of a natural; he\u2019s deeply committed to his character\" and that he also manages to \"infuse Elio with something of himself, too, as the best movie stars do\". He also writes that \"Chalamet seems to know that he\u2019s got an innate charm, a boyish grace, and he uses that to striking effect. Elio, soulful and impetuous and a little bratty, is a kid you\u2019ve known, a kid you wanted to be, a kid you care and root for\", before calling his portrayal of Elio \"a mature and thoughtful performance, and it augurs great things for Chalamet going forward\".\n\n===Performance recognition===\n\nAt the age of 21, Chalamet became the [[List of Academy Award records#Age-related records|youngest]] [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] nominee [[12th Academy Awards|since 1939]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-oscars-james-ivory-adapted-screenplay-20180304-story.html|work=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|title=James Ivory becomes Oscar's oldest winner with 'Call Me by Your Name'|date=March 4, 2018|accessdate=March 4, 2018|first1=Mark|last1=Olsen|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305162848/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-oscars-james-ivory-adapted-screenplay-20180304-story.html|archivedate=March 5, 2018}}</ref> in addition to nominations at [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|BAFTA]], the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globes]], the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild]], and a [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Critics' Choice Awards]] for Best Actor.\n\nAt the [[33rd Independent Spirit Awards]], Chalamet won the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Male Lead|Best Male Lead Award]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/PressReleasesSA/2018_SA_NomineeRelease_FINAL.pdf|title=33rd Film Independent Spirits Nominations Announced|publisher=[[Independent Spirit Awards]]|date=November 21, 2017|accessdate=November 21, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207071727/https://s3.amazonaws.com/PressReleasesSA/2018_SA_NomineeRelease_FINAL.pdf|archivedate=December 7, 2017|url-status=live|type=Press release|location=Los Angeles}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmindependent.org/press/press-releases/2018-film-independent-spirit-awards-winners-announced/|title=2018 Film Independent Spirit Awards Winners Announced|publisher=[[Independent Spirit Awards]]|date=March 3, 2018|location=Los Angeles|accessdate=March 3, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304021242/https://www.filmindependent.org/press/press-releases/2018-film-independent-spirit-awards-winners-announced/|archivedate=March 4, 2018|url-status=dead|type=Press release}}</ref> other accolades he won included; The [[National Board of Review]], the [[Gotham Independent Film Awards]] and the [[Hollywood Film Awards]] for Breakout Actor, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gettell|first1=Oliver|title=''Call Me By Your Name'' takes top prize at 2017 Gotham Awards|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/11/27/gotham-awards-2017-winners-list/|accessdate=November 27, 2017|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207224507/http://ew.com/movies/2017/11/27/gotham-awards-2017-winners-list/|archivedate=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodawards.com/2017-honorees/|title= 2017 Honorees|publisher=[[Hollywood Film Awards]]|accessdate=October 19, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022082519/https://www.hollywoodawards.com/2017-honorees/|archivedate=October 22, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[IndieWire]], in a series of articles regarding the best of film [[2010s in film|in the 2010s]], named Chalamet's portrayal of Elio as the 39th best film performance of the 2010s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/gallery/best-acting-movies-2010s-performances/|title=The 50 Best Movie Performances of the Decade|last=Zilko|first=David Ehrlich,Kate Erbland,Eric Kohn,Anne Thompson,Chris O'Falt,Tambay Obenson,Christian Blauvelt,Christian|last2=Ehrlich|first2=David|date=2019-07-23|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28|last3=Erbland|first3=Kate|last4=Kohn|first4=Eric|last5=Thompson|first5=Anne|last6=O'Falt|first6=Chris|last7=Obenson|first7=Tambay|last8=Blauvelt|first8=Christian|last9=Zilko|first9=Christian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Call Me by Your Name}}\n\n[[Category:Call Me by Your Name]]\n[[Category:Drama film characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional bisexual males]]\n[[Category:Fictional Jews]]\n[[Category:Fictional LGBT characters in film]]\n[[Category:Fictional LGBT characters in literature]]\n[[Category:Fictional musicians]]\n[[Category:Fictional North American people]]\n[[Category:Fictional pianists]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in literature]]\n", "name_user": "191.36.130.34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacterization:conte\u00fado adicionado)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elio_Perlman"}
{"title_page": "Sydney Hall (actor)", "text_new": "'''Sydney Hall''' is an American actor, model and dancer.\n\n==Education==\nHall completed his schooling at [[Northwest Catholic High School]] in [[West Hartford, Connecticut]] in 1991. He subsequently attended [[Howard University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], where he obtained a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]].<ref name=Logos>{{cite journal|title=Spotted on Screen \u2013 Sydney Hall '91|journal=Logos: The Magazine of Northwest Catholic High School|date=Fall 2010 \u2013 Winter 2011|page=6|url=http://issuu.com/nwcmagazine/docs/logos--fall10-winter11|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Parks|editor-first=Gregory S.|title=Alpha Phi Alpha: A Legacy of Greatness, The Demands of Transcendence|date=2012|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|location=Lexington|isbn=9780813134574|page=366|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kcKJ7LTWjm8C|accessdate=August 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==South Africa==\nIn 1994, Hall travelled to [[Soweto]] in [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]] as part of the Step Afrika! [[Stepping (African-American)|stepping]] dance troupe of fraternity brothers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Padgett|first1=Raven|title=Step Afrika!: 15 Years of Creating Cultural Conversations|journal=Howard University|date=Spring 2009|pages=24\u201325|url=http://howardmagazine.idigitaledition.com/issues/2/Page32/bypass/|access-date=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6S5TU1CEO?url=http://howardmagazine.idigitaledition.com/issues/2/Page32/bypass/|archive-date=August 25, 2014|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Malone|first1=Jacqui|title=Steppin' on the Blues: The Visible Rhythms of African American dance|date=2006|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana|isbn=9780252065088|page=166|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yWJXUnPDFk0C|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Norris|first1=Michele|title=Step Afrika|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1524911|accessdate=August 25, 2014|work=[[All Things Considered]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=November 28, 2003}}</ref> He lived in South Africa for several years, working as a model and actor. He also owned a nightclub there.<ref name=Logos/><ref name=Insider>{{cite web|title=Sydney Hall Interview|url=http://www.generationkillinsider.com/interviews.htm#709530380|website=Generation Kill Insider|access-date=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6S5XVXqGQ?url=http://www.generationkillinsider.com/interviews.htm#709530380|archive-date=August 25, 2014|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> He played the character Dr CL Phunk in a series of [[retro style|retro]] television commercials commencing in 2002 for the [[Chicken Licken (restaurant)|Chicken Licken]] fast-food restaurant chain.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dr Phunk se epiese TV-avontuur|url=http://152.111.1.88/argief/berigte/beeld/2005/07/11/B1/18/03.html|language=Afrikaans|trans-title=Dr Phunk's epic TV-adventure|access-date=August 23, 2014|work=Beeld|date=July 11, 2005|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6S2j3Lm0x?url=http://152.111.1.88/argief/berigte/beeld/2005/07/11/B1/18/03.html|archive-date=August 23, 2014|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Taunyane|first1=Molebogeng|title=A seasoned Chicken Licken|url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/citypress/2006/07/02/CG/4/01.html|access-date=August 23, 2014|work=City Press|date=July 2, 2006|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6S2idMS11?url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/citypress/2006/07/02/CG/4/01.html|archive-date=August 23, 2014|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Ron|title=South Africa: Dr Phunk's New Ads Cook Up Juicy Sales for Upwardly Mobile Chicken Licken|date=July 13, 2005|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200507130104.html|newspaper=Business Day|access-date=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6S5Rws6hz?url=http://allafrica.com/s