:African-American male models]]\n[[Category:African-American models]]\n[[Category:American male models]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-screen-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSouth Africa:added comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sydney_Hall_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Wesleyan Hall", "text_new": "{{container}}\n\n{{Infobox nrhp | name =Wesleyan Hall\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Bell-tower-wesleyan.JPG\n  | caption = \n  | location = Morrison Ave., [[Florence, Alabama]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|34|48|32|N|87|40|45|W|display=inline,title}}\n  | area =\n  | built = 1855\n  | architect = Morrison, Zebulon Pike\n  | architecture = Gothic Revival, Castellated sub-style\n  | added = June 20, 1974\n  | governing_body = State\n  | refnum=74000417\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Wesleyan Hall''', constructed in 1856, is one of the oldest structures on the [[University of North Alabama]] campus, located in [[Florence, Alabama]].\n\n==History==\n\nWith its distinctive towers, Wesleyan Hall also is considered one of the most eminent landmarks in [[North Alabama]]. The [[Gothic Revival]] structure was designed to serve LaGrange College when this Methodist institution relocated from Franklin to Lauderdale county and subsequently was renamed and rechartered as Florence Wesleyan University.<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\">[http://www2.una.edu/universityrelations/attractions.htm \"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions,\" Office of University Relations, University of North Alabama]</ref>\n\nIn 1856, the year the structure was completed, a President's Report showed an enrollment of 180 students. The fledgling university peaked at 225 students in the early 1860s, shortly before the outbreak of the [[U.S. Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\"The 175-Year March from the 19th Century into the 21st\">Steen, Robert S., \"The 175-Year March from the 19th into the 21st,\" UNA Magazine, Summer, 2005</ref>\n\nDuring the war, Wesleyan Hall was occupied by both Union and Confederate armies.<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\"/> \n[[Image:William Tecumseh Sherman.jpg|right|thumb|220px|General William Tecumseh Sherman is considered the most famous Union officer to occupy Wesleyan Hall during the Civil War.]]General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]] is considered the most famous Union occupant of Wesleyan Hall during the war.<ref name=\"Leo's Tale: University of North Alabama Trivia\">Smith, William E., \"Leo's Tale: University of North Alabama Trivia, Florence, AL, Shoals Heritage Publishers, 2000.</ref> In late 1864, shortly before his ill-fated involvement in the battles of [[Battle of Franklin|Franklin]] and [[Battle of Nashville|Nashville]], Confederate General [[John Bell Hood]] occupied the building.  The surrounding grounds were occupied by his troops and served as a meeting place for military personnel and townspeople for parties, dances and concerts.  Confederate Generals [[Pierre G.T. Beauregard]] and [[Stephen D. Lee]] also occupied the adjoining grounds during the war and also may have used Wesleyan Hall as their headquarters.\n\nFollowing the war, Dr. Septimus Rice was the University's sole instructor, teaching classes in the Preparatory School and holding college-level courses in Wesleyan Hall.  Despite a prolonged effort by the new Wesleyan University president, Dr. William H. Anderson, the institution continued to founder, and in 1871, the doors of Wesleyan Hall were closed.\n\nRecognizing the need for trained teachers in the post-war South, the Methodist Episcopal Church turned over Wesleyan Hall and the surrounding {{convert|12|acre|m2|adj=on}} grounds to the state of [[Alabama]], which then chartered it as a state [[normal school]].\n\nDuring this period, the halls of Wesleyan remained unheated, so stoves were used to warm classrooms, while coal oil lamps were employed for lighting. Because of the initially small enrollment, the upper floors were used as [[dormitory|dormitories]].\n\nA dilapidated white-washed board fence stood along the perimeter of the Wesleyan grounds to prevent livestock owned by nearby townspeople from wandering onto campus. On the south side of the structure in a similar state of disrepair stood a number of old stables used to quarter horses of local country boys attending the school. A large [[cistern]] in the rear of the Wesleyan supplied the school's water supply.\n\nAt the turn of the 20th century, the 45-year-old structure remained the only building owned by the school. The exterior of the building had changed little since its construction in 1856, bearing the same castle-like towers, battlements and top-floor [[observatory]]. Likewise, the campus adjoining Wesleyan encompassed only the original {{convert|12|acre|m2}}.\n\nA three-story building finally was added in 1909 to accommodate increased enrollment and became known as Wesleyan Annex.<ref name=\"The 175-Year March from the 19th Century into the 21st\"/>\n\n==Today==\n\nNow part of the {{convert|130|acre|km2|adj=on}} University of North Alabama campus, Wesleyan Hall currently contains the departments of Geography, Psychology, and Foreign Languages.  It also houses the Geographic Research Center, a cartography lab, and a language lab.\n\nThe Department of Military Science is located in Wesleyan Annex.\n\nWesleyan also houses personal effects and mementoes of former Alabama Supreme Court Chief Justice and U.S. Senator [[Howell Heflin]], a native of nearby Tuscumbia.  The building is listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\"/>\n\n==Wesleyan Bell and Tower==\n[[File:Wesleyan-una.jpg|thumb|Historic Wesleyan Hall, taken in 2004]]\nAdjacent to Wesleyan Hall in a specially constructed tower is the Wesleyan Bell, which tolled regularly throughout the last quarter of the 19th century to summon Florence Normal School students to class.  Sometime around 1910, the bell was removed from Wesleyan Hall and stored.  Rediscovered after the passage of almost a century in 2002, the 130-year-old Wesleyan Bell finally was restored to a prominent place on campus following construction of the Smith Bell Tower in 2004.<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Wesleyan Hall}}\n*[http://www.una.edu/ Official website]\n\n{{University of North Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Lauderdale County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:University of North Alabama campus]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in Alabama]]\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1855]]\n[[Category:University and college buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox_nrhp | name =Wesleyan Hall\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Bell-tower-wesleyan.JPG\n  | caption = \n  | location = Morrison Ave., [[Florence, Alabama]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|34|48|32|N|87|40|45|W|display=inline,title}}\n  | area =\n  | built = 1855\n  | architect = Morrison, Zebulon Pike\n  | architecture = Gothic Revival, Castellated sub-style\n  | added = June 20, 1974\n  | governing_body = State\n  | refnum=74000417\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Wesleyan Hall''', constructed in 1856, is one of the oldest structures on the [[University of North Alabama]] campus, located in [[Florence, Alabama]].  \n\n==History==\n\nWith its distinctive towers, Wesleyan Hall also is considered one of the most eminent landmarks in [[North Alabama]]. The [[Gothic Revival]] structure was designed to serve LaGrange College when this Methodist institution relocated from Franklin to Lauderdale county and subsequently was renamed and rechartered as Florence Wesleyan University.<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\">[http://www2.una.edu/universityrelations/attractions.htm \"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions,\" Office of University Relations, University of North Alabama]</ref>\n\nIn 1856, the year the structure was completed, a President's Report showed an enrollment of 180 students. The fledgling university peaked at 225 students in the early 1860s, shortly before the outbreak of the [[U.S. Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\"The 175-Year March from the 19th Century into the 21st\">Steen, Robert S., \"The 175-Year March from the 19th into the 21st,\" UNA Magazine, Summer, 2005</ref>\n\nDuring the war, Wesleyan Hall was occupied by both Union and Confederate armies.<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\"/> \n[[Image:William Tecumseh Sherman.jpg|right|thumb|220px|General William Tecumseh Sherman is considered the most famous Union officer to occupy Wesleyan Hall during the Civil War.]]General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]] is considered the most famous Union occupant of Wesleyan Hall during the war.<ref name=\"Leo's Tale: University of North Alabama Trivia\">Smith, William E., \"Leo's Tale: University of North Alabama Trivia, Florence, AL, Shoals Heritage Publishers, 2000.</ref> In late 1864, shortly before his ill-fated involvement in the battles of [[Battle of Franklin|Franklin]] and [[Battle of Nashville|Nashville]], Confederate General [[John Bell Hood]] occupied the building.  The surrounding grounds were occupied by his troops and served as a meeting place for military personnel and townspeople for parties, dances and concerts.  Confederate Generals [[Pierre G.T. Beauregard]] and [[Stephen D. Lee]] also occupied the adjoining grounds during the war and also may have used Wesleyan Hall as their headquarters. \n\nFollowing the war, Dr. Septimus Rice was the University's sole instructor, teaching classes in the Preparatory School and holding college-level courses in Wesleyan Hall.  Despite a prolonged effort by the new Wesleyan University president, Dr. William H. Anderson, the institution continued to founder, and in 1871, the doors of Wesleyan Hall were closed.  \n\nRecognizing the need for trained teachers in the post-war South, the Methodist Episcopal Church turned over Wesleyan Hall and the surrounding {{convert|12|acre|m2|adj=on}} grounds to the state of [[Alabama]], which then chartered it as a state [[normal school]].\n\nDuring this period, the halls of Wesleyan remained unheated, so stoves were used to warm classrooms, while coal oil lamps were employed for lighting. Because of the initially small enrollment, the upper floors were used as [[dormitory|dormitories]].\n\nA dilapidated white-washed board fence stood along the perimeter of the Wesleyan grounds to prevent livestock owned by nearby townspeople from wandering onto campus. On the south side of the structure in a similar state of disrepair stood a number of old stables used to quarter horses of local country boys attending the school. A large [[cistern]] in the rear of the Wesleyan supplied the school's water supply.\n\nAt the turn of the 20th century, the 45-year-old structure remained the only building owned by the school. The exterior of the building had changed little since its construction in 1856, bearing the same castle-like towers, battlements and top-floor [[observatory]]. Likewise, the campus adjoining Wesleyan encompassed only the original {{convert|12|acre|m2}}. \n\nA three-story building finally was added in 1909 to accommodate increased enrollment and became known as Wesleyan Annex.<ref name=\"The 175-Year March from the 19th Century into the 21st\">Steen, Robert S., \"The 175-Year March from the 19th into the 21st,\" UNA Magazine, Summer, 2005</ref>\n\n==Today==\n\nNow part of the {{convert|130|acre|km2|sing=on}} University of North Alabama campus, Wesleyan Hall currently contains the departments of Geography, Psychology, and Foreign Languages.  It also houses the Geographic Research Center, a cartography lab, and a language lab.  \n\nThe Department of Military Science is located in Wesleyan Annex.  \n\nWesleyan also houses personal effects and mementoes of former Alabama Supreme Court Chief Justice and U.S. Senator [[Howell Heflin]], a native of nearby Tuscumbia.  The building is listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\"/>\n\n==Wesleyan Bell and Tower==\n[[File:Wesleyan-una.jpg|thumb|Historic Wesleyan Hall, taken in 2004]]\nAdjacent to Wesleyan Hall in a specially constructed tower is the Wesleyan Bell, which tolled regularly throughout the last quarter of the 19th century to summon Florence Normal School students to class.  Sometime around 1910, the bell was removed from Wesleyan Hall and stored.  Rediscovered after the passage of almost a century in 2002, the 130-year-old Wesleyan Bell finally was restored to a prominent place on campus following construction of the Smith Bell Tower in 2004.<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\"/> \n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Wesleyan Hall}}\n*[http://www.una.edu/ Official website]\n\n{{University of North Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Lauderdale County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Alabama]]\n[[Category:University of North Alabama campus]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in Alabama]]\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1855]]\n[[Category:University and college buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wesleyan_Hall"}
{"title_page": "Wilhelm Traugott Krug", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2019}}\n[[File:Wilhelm Traugott Krug.jpg|thumb|Wilhelm Traugott Krug.]]\n'''Wilhelm Traugott Krug''' (22 June 1770{{snd}}12 January 1842) was a [[Germany|German]] philosopher and writer.\n\n==Life==\nKrug was born at [[Radis]] in [[Electorate of Saxony|Saxony]], and died at [[Leipzig]]. He studied at [[Wittenberg]] under [[Franz Volkmar Reinhard]] and Karl Gottfried Jehnichen, at [[Jena]] under [[Karl Leonhard Reinhold]], and at [[G\u00f6ttingen]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=930}}\n\nFrom 1801 to 1804 he was professor of philosophy at [[Frankfurt (Oder)]], after which he succeeded [[Immanuel Kant]] in the chair of logic and metaphysics at the [[University of K\u00f6nigsberg]]. From 1809 till his death he was professor of philosophy at the [[University of Leipzig]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=930}} He fought in the [[War of the Sixth Coalition|War of Liberation]] (1813\u201314) as captain of mounted chasseurs.\n\n==Views==\nIn philosophy his method was psychological; he attempted to explain the [[Id, ego and super-ego#Ego|Ego]] by examining the nature of its reflection upon the facts of consciousness. Being is known to us only through its presentation in [[consciousness]]; consciousness only in its relation to [[Being]]. Both Being and Consciousness, however, are immediately known to us, as also the relation existing between them. By this Transcendental Synthesis he proposed to reconcile [[Philosophical realism|Realism]] and [[Idealism]], and to destroy the traditional difficulty between transcendental, or pure, thought and things in themselves.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=930}}\n\nKrug challenged Schelling to deduce his quill or pen from [[German Idealism]]'s [[Philosophy of Nature]]. In so doing, he challenged the thinking that particular, perceptually real things could be logically known from general concepts.\n\n''Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte der Philos. des XIX. Jahrh.'' (1835\u20131837) contains criticisms of Hegel and [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling|Schelling]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=930}}\n\nHe was a prolific writer on a great variety of subjects, excelling as a popularizer rather than as an original thinker. His work stimulated freedom of thought in religion and politics,{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=930}} and he was a firm supporter of [[Jewish emancipation]].<ref>Gotthard Deutsch, S. Mannheimer, [http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/9534-krug-wilhelm-traugott# \"Krug, Wilhelm Traugott\"], ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'', 1906.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1804, Krug married [[Wilhelmine von Zenge]] (1780\u20131852), the eldest daughter of a Prussian major-general. They had six children. Wilhelmine had previously been engaged to [[Heinrich von Kleist]].<ref>[http://www.heinrich-von-kleist.org/en/heinrich-von-kleist/biography/ Heinrich von Kleist: Biography], Kleist Museum.</ref>\n\n==Principal works==\n*''Briefe \u00fcber den neuesten Idealismus'' (1801)\n*''Versuch \u00fcber die Principien der philosophischen Erkenntniss'' (1801)\n*''Fundamentalphilosophie'' (1803)\n*''System der theoretischen Philosophie'' (1806\u20131810)\n*''System der praktischen Philosophie'' (1817\u20131819)\n*''Handbuch der Philosophie'' (1820; 3rd ed., 1828)\n*''Logik oder Denklehre (1827)\n*''Geschichte der Philosophie alter Zeit'' (1815; 2nd ed., 1825)\n*''Allgemeines Handw\u00f6rterbuch der philosophischen Wissenschaften'' (1827-1834; 2nd ed., 1832-1838)\n*''Universal-philosophische Vorlesungen f\u00fcr Gebildete beiderei Geschlechts''\n*''Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte der Philos. des XIX. Jahrh.'' (1835\u20131837)\n*''Meine Lebensreise'' (Leipzig, 2nd ed.,1840), autobiography{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|pp=930\u2013931}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2014 }}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Krug, Wilhelm Traugott|volume=15|pages=930\u2013931}}\n*{{Cite NIE|wstitle=Krug, Wilhelm Traugott|year=1905}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krug, Wilhelm Traugott}}\n[[Category:1770 births]]\n[[Category:1842 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kemberg]]\n[[Category:People from the Electorate of Saxony]]\n[[Category:Members of the First Chamber of the Diet of the Kingdom of Saxony]]\n[[Category:German philosophers]]\n[[Category:19th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:German logicians]]\n[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of mind]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:University of Wittenberg alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Jena alumni]]\n[[Category:University of G\u00f6ttingen alumni]]\n[[Category:Viadrina European University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of K\u00f6nigsberg faculty]]\n[[Category:Leipzig University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=November 2019}}\n[[File:Wilhelm Traugott Krug.jpg|thumb|Wilhelm Traugott Krug.]]\n'''Wilhelm Traugott Krug''' (22 June 1770 \u2013 12 January 1842) was a [[Germany|German]] philosopher and writer.\n\n==Life==\nKrug was born at [[Radis]] in [[Electorate of Saxony|Saxony]], and died at [[Leipzig]]. He studied at [[Wittenberg]] under [[Franz Volkmar Reinhard]] and Karl Gottfried Jehnichen, at [[Jena]] under [[Karl Leonhard Reinhold]], and at [[G\u00f6ttingen]].\n\nFrom 1801 to 1804 he was professor of philosophy at [[Frankfurt (Oder)]], after which he succeeded [[Immanuel Kant]] in the chair of logic and metaphysics at the [[University of K\u00f6nigsberg]]. From 1809 till his death he was professor of philosophy at the [[University of Leipzig]]. He fought in the [[War of the Sixth Coalition|War of Liberation]] (1813\u201314) as captain of mounted chasseurs.\n\n==Views==\nIn philosophy his method was psychological; he attempted to explain the [[Id, ego and super-ego#Ego|Ego]] by examining the nature of its reflection upon the facts of consciousness. Being is known to us only through its presentation in [[consciousness]]; consciousness only in its relation to [[Being]]. Both Being and Consciousness, however, are immediately known to us, as also the relation existing between them. By this Transcendental Synthesis he proposed to reconcile [[Philosophical realism|Realism]] and [[Idealism]], and to destroy the traditional difficulty between transcendental, or pure, thought and things in themselves.\n\nKrug challenged Schelling to deduce his quill or pen from [[German Idealism]]'s [[Philosophy of Nature]]. In so doing, he challenged the thinking that particular, perceptually real things could be logically known from general concepts. \n\n''Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte der Philos. des XIX. Jahrh.'' (1835\u20131837) contains criticisms of Hegel and [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling|Schelling]].\n\nHe was a prolific writer on a great variety of subjects, excelling as a popularizer rather than as an original thinker. His work stimulated freedom of thought in religion and politics, and he was a firm supporter of [[Jewish emancipation]].<ref>Gotthard Deutsch, S. Mannheimer, [http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/9534-krug-wilhelm-traugott# \"Krug, Wilhelm Traugott\"], ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'', 1906.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1804, Krug married [[Wilhelmine von Zenge]] (1780-1852), the eldest daughter of a Prussian major-general. They had six children. Wilhelmine had previously been engaged to [[Heinrich von Kleist]].<ref>[http://www.heinrich-von-kleist.org/en/heinrich-von-kleist/biography/ Heinrich von Kleist: Biography], Kleist Museum.</ref>\n\n==Principal works==\n*''Briefe \u00fcber den neuesten Idealismus'' (1801)\n*''Versuch \u00fcber die Principien der philosophischen Erkenntniss'' (1801)\n*''Fundamentalphilosophie'' (1803)\n*''System der theoretischen Philosophie'' (1806-1810)\n*''System der praktischen Philosophie'' (1817-1819)\n*''Handbuch der Philosophie'' (1820; 3rd ed., 1828)\n*''Logik oder Denklehre (1827)\n*''Geschichte der Philosophie alter Zeit'' (1815; 2nd ed., 1825)\n*''Allgemeines Handw\u00f6rterbuch der philosophischen Wissenschaften'' (1827-1834; 2nd ed., 1832-1838)\n*''Universal-philosophische Vorlesungen f\u00fcr Gebildete beiderei Geschlechts''\n*''Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte der Philos. des XIX. Jahrh.'' (1835-1837)\n*''Meine Lebensreise'' (Leipzig, 2nd ed.,1840), autobiography\n\n==Notes==\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2014 }}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Krug, Wilhelm Traugott}}\n*{{Cite NIE|wstitle=Krug, Wilhelm Traugott|year=1905}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krug, Wilhelm Traugott}}\n[[Category:1770 births]]\n[[Category:1842 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kemberg]]\n[[Category:People from the Electorate of Saxony]]\n[[Category:Members of the First Chamber of the Diet of the Kingdom of Saxony]]\n[[Category:German philosophers]]\n[[Category:19th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:German logicians]]\n[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of mind]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:University of Wittenberg alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Jena alumni]]\n[[Category:University of G\u00f6ttingen alumni]]\n[[Category:Viadrina European University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of K\u00f6nigsberg faculty]]\n[[Category:Leipzig University faculty]]\n", "name_user": "DavidBrooks-AWB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Specific EB1911 attributions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilhelm_Traugott_Krug"}
{"title_page": "Rogers Hall", "text_new": "{{container}}\n\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Courtview\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Courtview 2010.jpg\n  | caption = The building in 2010.\n  | location= Court St., [[Florence, Alabama]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|34|48|21|N|87|40|46|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Alabama#USA\n  | built = {{Start date|1855}}\n  | architect = John Ballinger\n  | architecture = Greek Revival\n  | added = June 13, 1974\n  | area = {{convert|1|acre}}\n  | governing_body = State   \n  | refnum = 74000415<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Rogers Hall''', also known as '''Courtview''', is a three-story antebellum house at 500 Court Street in [[Florence, Alabama|Florence]], [[Alabama]].  It was built from 1854 to 1855.<ref name=\"nrhpnom\">{{cite web |url={{NRHP url|id=74000415}} |title=National Register of Historic Places nomination form: Rogers Hall/Courtview |last1=Howard |first1=M. B. |date=December 28, 1973 |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref>  It is one of the oldest historic landmarks on the [[University of North Alabama]] campus and one of the university's most distinctive structures.<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\">[http://www2.una.edu/universityrelations/attractions.htm \"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions,\" Office of University Relations, University of North Alabama] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616132248/http://www2.una.edu/universityrelations/attractions.htm |date=2007-06-16 }}</ref>  The building was recorded by the [[Historic American Buildings Survey]] from 1934\u201335.<ref name=\"habs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/al0258/ |title=Courtview, 505 North Court Street, University of North Alabama Campus, Florence, Lauderdale County, AL |publisher=Library of Congress |accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref>  It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on June 13, 1974.<ref name=\"nris\"/><ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]-style mansion was constructed for George Washington Foster, a prominent local with plantations in Alabama, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], and [[Mississippi]].<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/> Located at the summit of Court Street and the highest point in Florence, Foster named his residence Courtview.<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>  Because construction would result in the permanent obstruction of a major thoroughfare, Foster had to secure the approval of the [[Alabama Legislature]] before work could begin.  Permission was granted with the stipulation  that \"the beauty of the home justify the inconvenience caused the people of the city.\"<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\"/><ref name=\"Alumni\">Lyles, Carol, \"Rogers Hall is Your Alumni House,\" UNA Magazine, Summer, 2006</ref>  He had the grounds professionally landscaped by the Hastings firm out of [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]].<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>\n\nFoster died in 1878, with the property going to his daughter, Sarah Independence Foster, and her husband, Stirling Payne MacDonald.  MacDonald was a former captain in the [[Confederate Army]].<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>  According to the diary of Sarah Foster MacDonald, the grounds were occupied by camps of Confederate and Union soldiers during the [[American Civil War]].  [[Union Army]] officers, under the command of [[William Tecumseh Sherman]], stayed in house on November 3, 1863. Confederate generals [[P. G. T. Beauregard]], [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]] and [[Stephen D. Lee]] visited the home in 1864. General Forrest, his wife, and son stayed with the Foster family for several days.<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>\n\nCourtview was occupied by members of the Foster family until 1900, when it was sold to [[Emmet O'Neal]], a Wesleyan University alumnus who served as the 34th [[List of Governors of Alabama|Governor of Alabama]] from 1911 to 1915. After 1915, O'Neal lived in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] and rented out the building as a boarding house.  It was acquired by Thomas M. Rogers in 1922 and underwent significant restoration and remodeling.  The Rogers family sold the house in 1948 to Florence State Teachers College, now known as the University of North Alabama.<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>\n\nDuring the 1950s, the former residence was used as a guest house and for social events. The parlors on the first floor were used frequently for student meetings.  The dining room and adjoining rooms were used by faculty and members of the Florence community.  During the early 1980s, alumni, faculty and staff initiated \"Project Courtview\", a [[fund drive]] to restore Rogers Hall. Over  700 people volunteered their services.<ref name=\"Alumni\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.una.edu/ UNA website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Alabama}}\n{{University of North Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Lauderdale County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Greek Revival houses in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1855]]\n[[Category:University of North Alabama campus]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Courtview\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Courtview 2010.jpg\n  | caption = The building in 2010.\n  | location= Court St., [[Florence, Alabama]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|34|48|21|N|87|40|46|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Alabama#USA\n  | built = {{Start date|1855}}\n  | architect = John Ballinger\n  | architecture = Greek Revival\n  | added = June 13, 1974\n  | area = {{convert|1|acre}}\n  | governing_body = State   \n  | refnum = 74000415<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Rogers Hall''', also known as '''Courtview''', is a three-story antebellum house at 500 Court Street in [[Florence, Alabama|Florence]], [[Alabama]].  It was built from 1854 to 1855.<ref name=\"nrhpnom\">{{cite web |url={{NRHP url|id=74000415}} |title=National Register of Historic Places nomination form: Rogers Hall/Courtview |last1=Howard |first1=M. B. |date=December 28, 1973 |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref>  It is one of the oldest historic landmarks on the [[University of North Alabama]] campus and one of the university's most distinctive structures.<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\">[http://www2.una.edu/universityrelations/attractions.htm \"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions,\" Office of University Relations, University of North Alabama] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616132248/http://www2.una.edu/universityrelations/attractions.htm |date=2007-06-16 }}</ref>  The building was recorded by the [[Historic American Buildings Survey]] from 1934\u201335.<ref name=\"habs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/al0258/ |title=Courtview, 505 North Court Street, University of North Alabama Campus, Florence, Lauderdale County, AL |publisher=Library of Congress |accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref>  It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on June 13, 1974.<ref name=\"nris\"/><ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]-style mansion was constructed for George Washington Foster, a prominent local with plantations in Alabama, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], and [[Mississippi]].<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/> Located at the summit of Court Street and the highest point in Florence, Foster named his residence Courtview.<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>  Because construction would result in the permanent obstruction of a major thoroughfare, Foster had to secure the approval of the [[Alabama Legislature]] before work could begin.  Permission was granted with the stipulation  that \"the beauty of the home justify the inconvenience caused the people of the city.\"<ref name=\"UNA Public and Tourist Attractions\"/><ref name=\"Alumni\">Lyles, Carol, \"Rogers Hall is Your Alumni House,\" UNA Magazine, Summer, 2006</ref>  He had the grounds professionally landscaped by the Hastings firm out of [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]].<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>\n\nFoster died in 1878, with the property going to his daughter, Sarah Independence Foster, and her husband, Stirling Payne MacDonald.  MacDonald was a former captain in the [[Confederate Army]].<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>  According to the diary of Sarah Foster MacDonald, the grounds were occupied by camps of Confederate and Union soldiers during the [[American Civil War]].  [[Union Army]] officers, under the command of [[William Tecumseh Sherman]], stayed in house on November 3, 1863. Confederate generals [[P. G. T. Beauregard]], [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]] and [[Stephen D. Lee]] visited the home in 1864. General Forrest, his wife, and son stayed with the Foster family for several days.<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>\n\nCourtview was occupied by members of the Foster family until 1900, when it was sold to [[Emmet O'Neal]], a Wesleyan University alumnus who served as the 34th [[List of Governors of Alabama|Governor of Alabama]] from 1911 to 1915. After 1915, O'Neal lived in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] and rented out the building as a boarding house.  It was acquired by Thomas M. Rogers in 1922 and underwent significant restoration and remodeling.  The Rogers family sold the house in 1948 to Florence State Teachers College, now known as the University of North Alabama.<ref name=\"nrhpnom\"/>\n\nDuring the 1950s, the former residence was used as a guest house and for social events. The parlors on the first floor were used frequently for student meetings.  The dining room and adjoining rooms were used by faculty and members of the Florence community.  During the early 1980s, alumni, faculty and staff initiated \"Project Courtview\", a [[fund drive]] to restore Rogers Hall. Over  700 people volunteered their services.<ref name=\"Alumni\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.una.edu/ UNA website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Alabama}}\n{{University of North Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Lauderdale County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Greek Revival houses in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1855]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Alabama]]\n[[Category:University of North Alabama campus]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rogers_Hall"}
